{
  "What are the two main purposes of cell division in living organisms?": "",
  "Only to increase cell size": "",
  "To create energy for the organism": "",
  "Growth and repair of tissues (via mitosis), and sexual reproduction (via meiosis)": "",
  "Only to produce gametes": "",
  "Cell division serves two major purposes: (1) mitosis produces genetically identical cells for growth, development, and repair of tissues, and (2) meiosis produces gametes (sperm and egg) with half the chromosome number for sexual reproduction.": "",
  "What are the three stages of interphase, and what happens during each?": "",
  "S1, S2, S3 -- three synthesis phases for DNA, RNA, and protein production respectively": "",
  "Prophase, metaphase, anaphase -- the three mitotic stages occurring before cell division": "",
  "G₁ (cell growth and normal functions), S (DNA synthesis/replication), G₂ (final growth and preparation for mitosis)": "",
  "G1, G2, G3 -- three successive growth phases each lasting approximately equal time periods": "",
  "Interphase is the longest part of the cell cycle (~90% of time). G₁ (Gap 1): the cell grows, produces proteins, and carries out normal functions. S (Synthesis): DNA is replicated so each chromosome becomes two sister chromatids. G₂ (Gap 2): the cell continues to grow and synthesizes proteins needed for mitosis (e.g., tubulin for spindle fibers).": "",
  "During which phase of interphase does DNA replication occur?": "",
  "M phase, when the cell is actively undergoing mitotic division of nuclear material": "",
  "G1 phase, the first growth period when the cell increases in size and makes proteins": "",
  "S (synthesis) phase — each chromosome is copied to form two identical sister chromatids": "",
  "G2 phase, the final preparation stage before the cell enters mitotic division": "",
  "DNA replication occurs during the S (synthesis) phase of interphase. Before S phase, each chromosome consists of a single DNA molecule. After S phase, each chromosome consists of two identical sister chromatids joined at the centromere. This ensures each daughter cell will receive a complete copy of the genome.": "",
  "How many chromosomes are in a typical human somatic (body) cell?": "",
  "12 chromosomes total, arranged in 6 homologous pairs of matched maternal and paternal copies": "",
  "23 chromosomes total, which is the number found in human gametes after meiotic division": "",
  "92 chromosomes total, which represents the tetraploid condition found in some plant species": "",
  "46 chromosomes (23 pairs — 22 pairs of autosomes plus 1 pair of sex chromosomes)": "",
  "Human somatic cells are diploid (2n = 46), containing 23 pairs of chromosomes. Of these, 22 pairs are autosomes (non-sex chromosomes) and 1 pair are sex chromosomes (XX in females, XY in males). Gametes (sperm and egg) are haploid (n = 23), containing one chromosome from each pair.": "",
  "What are sister chromatids, and how are they connected?": "",
  "Two identical copies of a single chromosome, formed during S phase and joined at the centromere": "",
  "The two strands of a DNA double helix": "",
  "Different chromosomes from different parents": "",
  "Unrelated fragments of RNA": "",
  "Sister chromatids are identical copies of a single replicated chromosome, produced during S phase of interphase. They are joined at a constricted region called the centromere, which serves as the attachment point for spindle fibers during mitosis. Sister chromatids are separated during anaphase and distributed to daughter cells.": "",
  "How does cytokinesis differ between animal cells and plant cells?": "",
  "Both form a cell plate by fusing Golgi-derived vesicles at the center of the dividing cell": "",
  "Both use a cleavage furrow formed by contraction of the actin-myosin ring at the cell equator": "",
  "Animal cells: the cell membrane pinches inward (cleavage furrow); Plant cells: vesicles fuse to form a cell plate that becomes a new cell wall between daughter cells": "",
  "Animal cells form a cell plate from vesicles; plant cells use a cleavage furrow from actin contraction": "",
  "In animal cells, a contractile ring of actin and myosin filaments pinches the membrane inward, forming a cleavage furrow that deepens until the cell splits. In plant cells, the rigid cell wall prevents pinching, so Golgi-derived vesicles fuse at the midline to form a cell plate that develops into a new cell wall separating the daughter cells.": "",
  "What type of cell division do prokaryotes (bacteria) use to reproduce?": "",
  "Meiosis producing haploid cells that fuse during conjugation to restore the diploid chromosome number": "",
  "Budding exclusively, where a small copy of the organism grows off the parent cell wall surface": "",
  "Binary fission — the circular DNA replicates, the cell elongates, and a septum divides the cell into two identical daughter cells": "",
  "Mitosis with a spindle apparatus formed from centrioles and kinetochore microtubule attachments": "",
  "Prokaryotes lack a nucleus and membrane-bound organelles, so they cannot perform mitosis. Instead, they reproduce by binary fission: the single circular chromosome replicates, the two copies attach to the plasma membrane and move apart as the cell elongates, and a septum forms at the midpoint to divide the cell into two genetically identical daughter cells.": "",
  "What is the key advantage of sexual reproduction compared to asexual reproduction?": "",
  "It is faster and requires fewer resources, allowing rapid population growth in stable environments": "",
  "It requires only one parent, simplifying the reproductive process and reducing energy expenditure": "",
  "It produces genetic variation among offspring, increasing a population's ability to adapt to changing environments": "",
  "It always produces more offspring per reproductive cycle than any form of asexual reproduction can": "",
  "Sexual reproduction combines genetic material from two parents through meiosis and fertilization, creating offspring with unique combinations of alleles. This genetic variation is the raw material for natural selection, allowing populations to adapt to new diseases, predators, and environmental changes. Asexual reproduction is faster but produces clones with no genetic diversity.": "",
  "What happens to a cell's chromosome number after one complete round of mitosis and cytokinesis?": "",
  "The chromosome number stays the same — each daughter cell receives the identical set of chromosomes as the parent cell": "",
  "The chromosome number doubles because each chromosome is replicated during S phase of interphase": "",
  "The chromosome number is halved because sister chromatids are separated to different daughter cells": "",
  "The number varies randomly depending on which chromosomes are distributed during cell division": "",
  "Mitosis is an equational division — it produces two daughter cells that are genetically identical to the parent cell. Although DNA is duplicated during S phase (creating sister chromatids), the separation of chromatids during anaphase ensures each daughter cell receives exactly the same number and type of chromosomes as the original cell (2n → 2n in humans: 46 → 46).": "",
  "What are some methods of asexual reproduction found in living organisms?": "",
  "Only meiosis and fertilization, which are the exclusive methods of reproduction in all organisms": "",
  "Binary fission, budding, fragmentation, and vegetative propagation — all producing genetically identical offspring": "",
  "Crossing over and independent assortment, which shuffle genetic material during cell division": "",
  "Only mitosis in multicellular organisms, since unicellular organisms cannot reproduce asexually": "",
  "Asexual reproduction produces genetically identical offspring (clones) from a single parent. Methods include binary fission (bacteria), budding (yeast, hydra), fragmentation (starfish, flatworms — a piece breaks off and regenerates), and vegetative propagation (plants producing new individuals from roots, stems, or leaves). All bypass meiosis and fertilization.": "",
  "Which definition BEST describes the 'cell cycle'?": "",
  "The movement of cells through the bloodstream via the circulatory system to different body tissues": "",
  "The ordered sequence of events from one cell division to the next, consisting of interphase (G₁, S, G₂) and M phase (mitosis and cytokinesis)": "",
  "The recycling of dead cells by the immune system through phagocytosis and lysosomal degradation": "",
  "The process of DNA unwinding for transcription by RNA polymerase during gene expression in interphase": "",
  "The cell cycle is a precisely regulated sequence of events that a cell undergoes from one division to the next. It consists of interphase (G₁ for growth, S for DNA synthesis, G₂ for preparation) and M phase (mitosis — division of the nucleus — followed by cytokinesis — division of the cytoplasm). Checkpoints at G₁/S, G₂/M, and the spindle assembly checkpoint ensure accuracy.": "",
  "Which definition BEST describes 'interphase'?": "",
  "The phase when the cell is actively dividing its nucleus": "",
  "The longest phase of the cell cycle during which the cell grows, carries out normal functions, and replicates its DNA in preparation for division (G₁ → S → G₂)": "",
  "The brief moment when chromosomes are visible under a microscope": "",
  "A phase where the cell shrinks and prepares to die": "",
  "Interphase occupies approximately 90% of the cell cycle. Despite once being called a 'resting phase,' the cell is highly active — synthesizing proteins, growing organelles (G₁), replicating all DNA (S phase), and producing materials needed for mitosis like tubulin (G₂). The cell is NOT dividing during interphase.": "",
  "Which definition BEST describes a 'chromosome'?": "",
  "A protein that catalyzes chemical reactions in cells, lowering the activation energy of metabolism": "",
  "A tightly coiled structure of DNA wrapped around histone proteins, visible during cell division; humans have 46 chromosomes (23 pairs) in each somatic cell": "",
  "A single strand of RNA found in the cytoplasm that carries genetic information from DNA to ribosomes": "",
  "A membrane-bound organelle that produces energy through oxidative phosphorylation in eukaryotic cells": "",
  "Chromosomes are structures made of DNA tightly wound around histone proteins, forming chromatin that condenses into visible chromosomes during cell division. Each human somatic cell contains 46 chromosomes (22 pairs of autosomes + 1 pair of sex chromosomes). Before S phase, each chromosome is a single chromatid; after S phase, each is two identical sister chromatids joined at the centromere.": "",
  "Which definition BEST describes a 'chromatid'?": "",
  "A permanent structural component of the nucleus that maintains the shape of the nuclear envelope": "",
  "A type of cell found only in bone marrow that gives rise to red and white blood cell lineages": "",
  "One copy of a duplicated chromosome; after DNA replication, two identical sister chromatids are joined at the centromere until they are separated during anaphase": "",
  "A type of pigment molecule in chloroplasts that captures light energy during the photosynthetic process": "",
  "After DNA replication in S phase, each chromosome consists of two identical sister chromatids connected at the centromere. During anaphase of mitosis, the centromere splits and the sister chromatids are pulled to opposite poles by spindle fibers. Once separated, each chromatid is considered an individual chromosome.": "",
  "Which definition BEST describes the 'centromere'?": "",
  "The point where a nerve impulse jumps between neurons at the synaptic cleft during signal transmission": "",
  "The central vacuole of a plant cell that maintains turgor pressure and stores water and nutrients": "",
  "The specialized constricted region of a chromosome where the two sister chromatids are joined, and where kinetochore proteins assemble to attach spindle fibers during cell division": "",
  "The center of the cell where the nucleus is located and all genetic information is stored and processed": "",
  "The centromere is the constricted region of a chromosome where sister chromatids are held together by cohesin proteins. Kinetochore protein complexes assemble on the centromere and serve as the attachment site for spindle microtubules. Proper centromere–kinetochore–spindle attachment is monitored by the spindle assembly checkpoint to prevent chromosome missegregation.": "",
  "Which definition BEST describes 'cytokinesis'?": "",
  "The condensation of chromatin into visible chromosomes that occurs during prophase of mitotic division": "",
  "The process of DNA replication during S phase that produces two identical copies of each chromosome": "",
  "The division of the cytoplasm following nuclear division (mitosis), resulting in two separate daughter cells — accomplished by a cleavage furrow in animal cells or a cell plate in plant cells": "",
  "The alignment of chromosomes at the metaphase plate, where spindle fibers attach to kinetochore proteins": "",
  "Cytokinesis is the physical division of the cytoplasm that follows mitosis (karyokinesis). In animal cells, a contractile ring of actin and myosin creates a cleavage furrow that pinches the cell in two. In plant cells, Golgi-derived vesicles fuse at the cell equator to form a cell plate that develops into a new cell wall.": "",
  "Which definition BEST describes 'binary fission'?": "",
  "The method of asexual reproduction used by prokaryotes, in which the circular DNA is replicated, the cell elongates, and a septum divides the cell into two genetically identical daughter cells": "",
  "The separation of sister chromatids during anaphase of mitosis, pulled apart by shortening spindle fibers": "",
  "The fusion of two gametes to form a zygote during sexual reproduction in multicellular organisms": "",
  "A type of nuclear division that produces four haploid cells from one diploid parent cell during meiosis": "",
  "Binary fission is how bacteria and archaea reproduce. The single circular chromosome attaches to the plasma membrane, replicates, and the two copies are separated as the cell elongates. A septum (cross-wall) then forms to divide the cell into two identical daughter cells. This process is simpler and faster than mitosis — some bacteria can divide every 20 minutes.": "",
  "Which definition BEST describes 'chromatin'?": "",
  "The complex of DNA wrapped around histone proteins found in the nucleus during interphase; it exists in a less condensed (extended) form that allows gene expression and DNA replication": "",
  "A pigment molecule in the chloroplast that absorbs light energy for use in the photosynthetic reactions": "",
  "The tightly condensed, visible form of DNA seen during cell division when chromosomes are at their most compact": "",
  "A type of RNA that carries genetic information from the nucleus to the ribosomes for translation": "",
  "Chromatin is the DNA-histone protein complex that fills the nucleus during interphase. In its extended (euchromatin) form, genes can be accessed for transcription and the DNA can be replicated during S phase. When the cell enters mitosis, chromatin condenses into the compact, visible structures we call chromosomes, which allows safe distribution of DNA to daughter cells.": "",
  "Which definition BEST describes 'spindle fibers'?": "",
  "Actin filaments responsible for muscle contraction and cellular movement through microfilament networks": "",
  "Microtubule structures that form during cell division, extending from centrioles (or MTOCs) to attach to kinetochores at chromosome centromeres and pull chromosomes to opposite poles of the cell": "",
  "Protein filaments that make up the cytoskeleton during interphase only and disassemble before cell division": "",
  "RNA molecules that guide ribosomes during translation by providing the template for protein synthesis": "",
  "Spindle fibers (mitotic spindle) are composed of microtubules — polymers of tubulin protein. They form from centrosomes (or MTOCs in plant cells) during prophase. Kinetochore microtubules attach to chromosome centromeres and shorten during anaphase to pull sister chromatids apart. The spindle assembly checkpoint ensures all chromosomes are properly attached before anaphase proceeds.": "",
  "Which definition BEST describes the 'G₀ phase'?": "",
  "The initial phase of cell death (apoptosis) when the cell begins to shrink and fragment its DNA": "",
  "The phase when cells undergo DNA repair only, fixing mutations before re-entering the active cycle": "",
  "The gap between S phase and M phase where the cell prepares for division by synthesizing division proteins": "",
  "A quiescent (resting) state in which a cell has exited the active cell cycle and is not preparing to divide — some cells remain in G₀ permanently (e.g., mature neurons, cardiac muscle cells)": "",
  "G₀ is a non-dividing state that cells enter when they leave G₁ of the cell cycle. Some cells (neurons, skeletal muscle fibers, red blood cells) are permanently in G₀. Others (hepatocytes, lymphocytes) are in G₀ but can re-enter the cell cycle in response to signals such as growth factors or tissue damage.": "",
  "A child scrapes their knee, removing a patch of skin cells. Over the following days, the wound closes and new skin cells fill the gap. What cellular process is primarily responsible for this tissue repair, and what phase of the cell cycle must the surrounding cells enter?": "",
  "Binary fission; skin cells split like bacteria using a septum that forms at the middle of the cell": "",
  "Apoptosis; damaged cells die and are not replaced, leaving the wound to heal by scar tissue formation": "",
  "Mitosis; surrounding cells that were in G₀ or G₁ are stimulated by growth factors to re-enter the cell cycle and divide, producing genetically identical replacement cells": "",
  "Meiosis; the cells need to produce gametes that develop into specialized skin cells at the wound site": "",
  "Wound healing relies on mitosis. When skin is damaged, platelets form a clot, immune cells clear debris, and growth factors (like EGF and PDGF) stimulate neighboring epithelial cells to leave G₀/G₁ and re-enter the cell cycle. These cells undergo mitosis to produce genetically identical daughter cells that migrate to fill the wound, restoring the tissue barrier.": "",
  "A biopsy reveals that a patient's lung cells are dividing uncontrollably, ignoring signals to stop. The cells have a mutated p53 gene (a tumor suppressor) and show abnormal chromosome numbers. What has gone wrong with the cell cycle, and why does this lead to cancer?": "",
  "The cells are in G₀ phase and cannot divide": "",
  "Cancer results from accumulated mutations in cell cycle regulatory genes. The p53 protein normally acts as the 'guardian of the genome' — at the G₁/S checkpoint, p53 halts division when DNA damage is detected so repairs can be made, or triggers apoptosis if the damage is irreparable. With p53 mutated, damaged cells skip this checkpoint and continue dividing, accumulating chromosomal abnormalities (aneuploidy). Multiple mutations in tumor suppressors and proto-oncogenes (Knudson's two-hit hypothesis) are typically required for full cancer development.": "",
  "After a patient undergoes partial hepatectomy (surgical removal of ~60% of their liver), the remaining liver regenerates to nearly its original mass within weeks. What cellular mechanism drives this remarkable regeneration, and what signals initiate it?": "",
  "Stem cells from bone marrow replace the lost liver tissue by traveling through the bloodstream to the organ": "",
  "The remaining liver cells simply enlarge without dividing, filling the space left by the removed tissue mass": "",
  "Mitosis; hepatocytes (normally in G₀) re-enter the cell cycle in response to growth factors like HGF (hepatocyte growth factor) and EGF (epidermal growth factor), undergoing compensatory hyperplasia": "",
  "Meiosis; the liver produces gametes that develop into new hepatocyte tissue to restore organ function": "",
  "Liver regeneration is a classic example of compensatory hyperplasia. After hepatectomy, cytokines (TNF-α, IL-6) prime hepatocytes, and growth factors (HGF, EGF, TGF-α) stimulate them to leave G₀ and re-enter the cell cycle. Hepatocytes undergo one or two rounds of mitosis — enough to restore the original liver mass. Once the proper mass is reached, TGF-β and other inhibitory signals halt further division.": "",
  "A cytogeneticist adds colchicine to a blood sample to prepare a karyotype. The cells are arrested in metaphase with condensed, visible chromosomes. How does colchicine achieve this, and why is metaphase arrest useful for karyotyping?": "",
  "Colchicine causes chromosomes to replicate extra copies for easier counting under the light microscope": "",
  "Colchicine speeds up cell division so more chromosomes can be photographed in their condensed visible state": "",
  "Colchicine stains chromosomes so they glow under UV light, making them visible for karyotype analysis": "",
  "Colchicine binds tubulin and prevents spindle microtubule assembly, arresting cells in metaphase when chromosomes are maximally condensed and aligned — ideal for photographing and arranging into a karyotype": "",
  "Colchicine blocks microtubule polymerization by binding free tubulin dimers, preventing spindle formation. Without a spindle, the spindle assembly checkpoint (SAC) is never satisfied, so cells remain arrested in metaphase — the stage when chromosomes are most condensed and visible. The arrested cells are then fixed, stained (e.g., Giemsa banding), and photographed to create a karyotype for detecting chromosomal abnormalities like trisomies or translocations.": "",
  "A starfish loses an arm to a predator and regenerates a complete new arm over several months. What role does mitosis play in this regeneration, and how does it differ from the way humans heal wounds?": "",
  "The arm regrows by cell enlargement without any cell division, as existing cells expand to fill the space": "",
  "The starfish uses meiosis to produce new arm cells from gametes that differentiate into arm tissue": "",
  "New cells arrive from other parts of the body via the circulatory system to rebuild the missing arm": "",
  "Mitosis at the wound site produces a blastema (mass of undifferentiated cells) that then differentiates into all the tissues of a new arm — unlike humans, who can repair tissues but cannot regenerate entire limbs": "",
  "Starfish (sea stars) demonstrate epimorphic regeneration. After amputation, cells at the wound site dedifferentiate and proliferate via mitosis to form a blastema — an undifferentiated cell mass. Blastema cells then redifferentiate into muscle, nerve, skeletal, and other tissues, guided by positional signaling molecules. Humans lack this ability for complex structures; our wound healing primarily involves mitosis of existing differentiated cells to close wounds and form scar tissue.": "",
  "A cancer patient is treated with vincristine, a chemotherapy drug derived from the periwinkle plant. How does vincristine disrupt cancer cell division, and how does its mechanism compare to colchicine?": "",
  "Like colchicine, vincristine binds tubulin and prevents microtubule assembly, blocking spindle formation and arresting cells in mitosis — the spindle assembly checkpoint triggers apoptosis in the arrested cancer cells": "",
  "Vincristine stabilizes microtubules so they cannot disassemble, which is the opposite mechanism of colchicine": "",
  "Vincristine destroys the cell DNA so it cannot replicate, inducing apoptosis through the p53 pathway": "",
  "Vincristine targets only the G1 phase of the cell cycle, preventing cells from entering S phase": "",
  "Vincristine (a vinca alkaloid) binds tubulin dimers at a different site than colchicine but with the same effect — preventing microtubule polymerization and blocking spindle assembly. Without a functional spindle, dividing cells arrest in mitosis and the prolonged SAC activation ultimately triggers apoptosis. Note: Taxol (paclitaxel) works OPPOSITELY — it stabilizes microtubules, preventing their disassembly, which also blocks mitosis. Both approaches exploit the cell's dependence on dynamic microtubules for division.": "",
  "Henrietta Lacks' cervical cancer cells (HeLa cells) have been dividing in laboratory culture continuously since 1951 — over 70 years. Normal human cells stop dividing after about 50 divisions (the Hayflick limit). What allows HeLa cells to bypass this limit?": "",
  "HeLa cells have fewer chromosomes, making division easier and faster than in normal somatic cell lineages": "",
  "HeLa cells do not need nutrients to divide because they generate their own energy through novel metabolism": "",
  "HeLa cells express high levels of telomerase, an enzyme that rebuilds telomeres after each division, preventing the shortening that normally triggers cellular senescence after ~50 divisions": "",
  "The cells undergo meiosis instead of mitosis, which allows unlimited division by resetting telomere length": "",
  "Normal somatic cells have low or no telomerase activity. With each mitotic division, telomeres (protective TTAGGG repeat caps on chromosome ends) shorten because DNA polymerase cannot fully replicate the 3' end. After ~50 divisions (Hayflick limit), critically short telomeres trigger p53-mediated senescence or apoptosis. Cancer cells like HeLa reactivate telomerase, which adds telomere repeats after each division, enabling unlimited proliferation — a hallmark of cancer (immortalization).": "",
  "The human body produces approximately 200 billion red blood cells every day. These cells originate from hematopoietic stem cells in the bone marrow. What role does the spindle assembly checkpoint (SAC) play in ensuring these rapidly dividing cells maintain the correct chromosome number?": "",
  "The SAC removes excess chromosomes from cells that have divided too many times, preventing polyploidy": "",
  "The SAC determines which cells become red blood cells versus white blood cells through lineage commitment": "",
  "The SAC speeds up cell division to meet the demand for new red blood cells during periods of high turnover": "",
  "The SAC monitors kinetochore-microtubule attachments during metaphase and delays anaphase onset until every chromosome is properly attached to spindle fibers from both poles, preventing aneuploidy in rapidly dividing bone marrow cells": "",
  "The spindle assembly checkpoint is critical in rapidly dividing tissues like bone marrow. The SAC protein complex (Mad1, Mad2, BubR1, Bub3) monitors each kinetochore. Unattached or incorrectly attached kinetochores generate a 'wait' signal that inhibits the anaphase-promoting complex (APC/C), preventing separation of sister chromatids. Only when ALL kinetochores achieve proper bipolar attachment does the SAC signal dissipate, allowing APC/C to trigger anaphase.": "",
  "A gardener takes a cutting from a prize-winning rose bush and grows an entirely new, genetically identical plant. What type of reproduction is this, what cellular process underlies the growth, and how does the genetic outcome compare to growing roses from seeds?": "",
  "Sexual reproduction using meiosis; the new plant is genetically unique": "",
  "Asexual reproduction (vegetative propagation) using mitosis; the new plant is a genetic clone of the parent, unlike seed-grown roses which are genetically unique due to meiosis and fertilization": "",
  "Sexual reproduction using mitosis; the new plant is identical to both parents": "",
  "Asexual reproduction using meiosis; the new plant has half the chromosomes": "",
  "Vegetative propagation (cuttings, grafting, runners, tubers) is asexual reproduction — new individuals arise from mitotic divisions of somatic cells, producing genetic clones (identical genotype). Seeds result from sexual reproduction (meiosis → gametes → fertilization), producing genetically unique offspring due to crossing over and independent assortment. Cloning via cuttings preserves desirable traits but reduces genetic diversity, making clonal populations vulnerable to disease.": "",
  "A single E. coli bacterium is placed in a nutrient-rich medium at 37°C. The bacterium divides by binary fission every 20 minutes. How many bacteria will be present after 4 hours (12 generations), and why might antibiotic resistance spread rapidly through a bacterial population that reproduces this way?": "",
  "2¹² = 4,096 bacteria; because binary fission produces genetically identical copies, a single mutation conferring antibiotic resistance is passed to ALL descendants, rapidly producing a resistant population": "",
  "12 bacteria; each generation adds one new cell to the population through linear rather than exponential growth": "",
  "4,096 bacteria; but resistance cannot spread because bacteria reproduce asexually and share no genetic material": "",
  "24 bacteria; mutations cannot occur during binary fission because the replication process is perfectly faithful": "",
  "Binary fission doubles the population with each generation: 1 → 2 → 4 → 8 → ... → 2¹² = 4,096 after 12 generations (4 hours). Since binary fission is asexual (no genetic recombination), daughter cells are clones. If one bacterium acquires an antibiotic resistance mutation (via random DNA replication error), all its descendants inherit the resistance. Additionally, bacteria can share resistance genes through horizontal gene transfer (conjugation, transformation, transduction), further accelerating resistance spread.": ""
}